Hereâ€™s a clear and concise description of the workflow for your setup using Spark + dbt + Iceberg + Nessie + MinIO:

â¸»

âœ… Workflow: Oracle to Iceberg using Spark + dbt

ðŸ”· 1. Data Source: Oracle (OLTP DB)
	â€¢	Your transactional data is stored in multiple tables in an Oracle database.
	â€¢	These tables represent the raw data needed for analytics.

â¸»

ðŸ”· 2. Data Transformation: Apache Spark
	â€¢	Spark (running via Docker) connects to Oracle using the JDBC connector.
	â€¢	It reads Oracle tables into Spark DataFrames.
	â€¢	Spark performs transformations using logic defined in dbt models.
	â€¢	All computation is done in-memory using Sparkâ€™s distributed engine.

â¸»

ðŸ”· 3. Materialization Target: Iceberg Table (Lakehouse)
	â€¢	Transformed data is written in Iceberg table format using Sparkâ€™s Iceberg connector.
	â€¢	Files are stored in MinIO (S3-compatible object store).
	â€¢	Table metadata (schema, versions, etc.) is managed via Nessie catalog.

â¸»

ðŸ”· 4. Transformation Orchestration: dbt
	â€¢	You define transformation models using SQL in your models/ folder.
	â€¢	dbt (outside Docker) connects to Spark via the Spark Thrift Server or native session.
	â€¢	On running dbt run:
	â€¢	dbt compiles SQL models.
	â€¢	Sends them to Spark to execute.
	â€¢	Spark writes the final Iceberg tables to MinIO and registers them with Nessie.

â¸»

ðŸ”· 5. Data Consumption: Analytics Layer
	â€¢	Tools like Trino, DuckDB, or Power BI can connect to the Nessie catalog via Iceberg to read final tables.
	â€¢	Querying happens without touching the Oracle system again.

â¸»

ðŸ” Optional CDC / Incremental:
	â€¢	You can configure dbt models as incremental, where Spark only processes new or changed data using timestamps or unique keys.

â¸»

